  "nursesNote": "Low self-esteem and disturbed body image can follow surgery (such as mastectomy, amputation, or an ostomy), chronic illness, eating disorders, or depression. Signs include negative self-talk, social withdrawal, avoiding looking at or touching a changed body part, and refusing to take part in care. The nurse builds a trusting relationship, accepts the patient's feelings, and encourages the patient to express feelings and grieve the change. The patient is gently encouraged to look at and care for the changed body part at their own pace. Feedback should be genuine and specific rather than false praise, which the patient will not believe. The nurse sets realistic, achievable goals to build success, focuses on the patient's strengths and abilities, promotes independence, involves the patient in care and decisions, and connects them to support groups.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Build trust and accept the patient's feelings",
    "Encourage expression of feelings and grieving",
    "Encourage gradual viewing and care of the changed body part",
    "Give genuine, specific feedback (not false praise)",
    "Set realistic goals and focus on strengths"
  ],
